&lt;h1 class="relative group">The Paradox of Paths
&lt;div id="the-paradox-of-paths" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#the-paradox-of-paths" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>When we’re learning or exploring,&lt;br>
whether it’s a new skill, a career move,&lt;br>
or simply life itself,&lt;br>
we often crave certainty.&lt;br>
We want a map, a list of steps, a clear destination.&lt;br>
But here’s the paradox:&lt;br>
sometimes, knowing too much holds us back,&lt;br>
while not knowing enough pushes us forward.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Four Ways Or One Way</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/four-ways-or-one-way/</link><pubDate>Wed, 27 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/four-ways-or-one-way/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5092-Four-Ways-Or-One-Way.jpg" alt="Four Ways Or One Way" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Four Ways Or One Way
&lt;div id="four-ways-or-one-way" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#four-ways-or-one-way" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>Generally, people think, &lt;br>
Bhakti Yoga, Karma Yoga, &lt;br>
Raj Yoga, Gyana Yoga &lt;br>
are the four parallel paths in life, &lt;br>
which leads to the same goal. &lt;br>
Hence, they think to walk on any road, &lt;br>
and we will reach the same place.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>If you like road analogy &lt;br>
then know it as only one road, &lt;br>
which you travel with four kinds of wealth. &lt;br>
Every moment, every day, and phase of life &lt;br>
based on the need you use &lt;br>
different wealth and keep moving.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>